00:50:18.980 --> 00:50:21.100
starts beeping like a banshee.

00:50:21.100 --> 00:50:23.660
And I'm thinking Spanish to blooms, right?

00:50:23.660 --> 00:50:25.460
And then suddenly, I'm shocked

00:50:25.460 --> 00:50:28.700
to see your mother's beautiful face blinking beneath me.

00:50:28.700 --> 00:50:31.300
And I'm thinking, what the Sam Hill?

00:50:31.300 --> 00:50:33.620
When your mother says, go ahead, honey.

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:34.580
Say it.

00:50:34.580 --> 00:50:35.700
It's me.

00:50:35.700 --> 00:50:38.620
I have a metal plate in my head.

00:50:38.620 --> 00:50:39.740
Can you believe that?

00:50:39.740 --> 00:50:43.100
A metal plate for some accident she had when she was a kid.

00:50:43.100 --> 00:50:44.540
We get to talk in.

00:50:44.540 --> 00:50:47.380
Next thing you know, honey, next thing you know.

00:50:47.380 --> 00:50:52.320
Wedding bells are ringing.

00:50:52.320 --> 00:50:53.760
Turn that thing off now.

00:50:53.760 --> 00:50:55.400
Sure, sorry.

00:50:55.400 --> 00:50:58.200
Did I ever tell you guys that story before?

00:50:58.200 --> 00:51:00.200
Huh?

00:51:00.200 --> 00:51:01.960
Before being launched into the story

00:51:01.960 --> 00:51:05.040
of their wild honeymoon at the Hoover Dam,

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:07.520
I veered toward the boardwalk, hoping I'd

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:13.480
find an ice cream man with some answers about Mr. Tasty.

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:15.120
What can I get you, son?

00:51:15.120 --> 00:51:17.360
How about a sludge sickle?

00:51:17.360 --> 00:51:19.720
You seem like a bona fide sludge sickle man.

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:21.600
You don't have any blue tornado bars, do you?

00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:22.680
Nope.

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:24.520
No, I don't.

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:26.000
You'll have to talk to Mr. Tasty

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:27.960
if it's a blue tornado you're after.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:29.520
Do you know where I can find him?

00:51:29.520 --> 00:51:30.960
Nope.

00:51:30.960 --> 00:51:34.600
He already got run out of town by a bunch of nosy kids.

00:51:34.600 --> 00:51:36.520
I heard they just wanted to be his friends.

00:51:36.520 --> 00:51:37.960
So that's what happened.

00:51:37.960 --> 00:51:39.120
What do you mean?

00:51:39.120 --> 00:51:40.680
Tasty nosy rules.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:44.160
Why do you think he wears that plastic head all the time?

00:51:44.160 --> 00:51:47.400
To keep kids like you from asking too many personal

00:51:47.400 --> 00:51:48.360
questions.

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:49.480
Why?

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:51.680
What do you guys so afraid of?

00:51:51.680 --> 00:51:54.640
Look, aren't we here on the first hot day

00:51:54.640 --> 00:51:56.080
of every summer?

00:51:56.080 --> 00:51:57.120
Aren't we?

00:51:57.120 --> 00:52:00.240
Don't we carry 49 different flavorific flavors,

00:52:00.240 --> 00:52:02.680
including pineapple, alert?

00:52:02.680 --> 00:52:12.010
What else do you want from us?

00:52:12.010 --> 00:52:15.220
I don't know anymore.

00:52:15.220 --> 00:52:17.380
How about that sludge sickle?

00:52:17.380 --> 00:52:23.840
Like I said, you look like a bona fide sludge sickle man.

00:52:23.840 --> 00:52:26.280
I had come hoping for a miracle.

00:52:26.280 --> 00:52:29.680
Instead, all I got was a cruddy sludge sickle

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:34.200
and a sinking feeling that Mr. Tasty was gone for good.

00:52:34.200 --> 00:52:49.230
We got something, something, something here, something big.

00:52:49.230 --> 00:52:51.510
Hey, hey, I think it's like an old reveal.

00:52:51.510 --> 00:52:55.350
You don't look like a Delta 88 or maybe a Cutlass Supreme.

00:53:00.870 --> 00:53:02.430
We all pitched in.

00:53:02.430 --> 00:53:05.150
And within the hour, we were the proud owners

00:53:05.150 --> 00:53:07.350
of a 1978 Cutlass Supreme.

00:53:16.410 --> 00:53:18.130
All right, buckle up.

00:53:18.130 --> 00:53:21.740
Let's go.

00:53:21.740 --> 00:53:25.580
It ran perfectly and had tons of leg room.

00:53:25.580 --> 00:53:27.020
I got a new guy.

00:53:27.020 --> 00:53:30.220
Our dad was so happy, he sang all the way home.

00:53:30.220 --> 00:53:31.980
I got a Cutlass Supreme.

00:53:31.980 --> 00:53:34.780
It's got a radio.

00:53:34.780 --> 00:53:36.860
Windows, headlights.

00:53:36.860 --> 00:53:39.900
As much as I enjoyed dad's beautiful voice,

00:53:39.900 --> 00:53:42.460
I knew Ellen was finishing her second shift.

00:53:42.460 --> 00:53:44.580
So I had dad drop me off at the mall.

00:53:44.580 --> 00:53:46.100
So hot to go at the beach.

00:53:46.100 --> 00:53:48.780
Dad found a car, Cutlass Supreme.

00:53:48.780 --> 00:53:50.700
Did you find anybody who knows Tasty?

00:53:50.700 --> 00:53:52.980
Yeah, this guy captain's from me.

00:53:52.980 --> 00:53:53.900
What'd he say?

00:53:53.900 --> 00:53:59.780
He said I looked like a bona fide sludge circle, Matt.

00:53:59.780 --> 00:54:02.580
Mr. Tasty's never coming back, is he?

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:05.380
No, I don't think so.

00:54:05.380 --> 00:54:05.780
Let's go.

00:54:05.780 --> 00:54:11.470
I'll walk you home.

00:54:11.470 --> 00:54:13.750
There was nothing left to do.

00:54:13.750 --> 00:54:16.830
He probably had found himself a new town where nobody

00:54:16.830 --> 00:54:19.110
knew how lonely he was.

00:54:19.110 --> 00:54:24.380
Our search for Mr. Tasty had come to a close.

00:54:24.380 --> 00:54:27.620
Pete refused to give up his post at first.

00:54:27.620 --> 00:54:29.660
But one chilly night in early September.

00:54:29.740 --> 00:54:32.060
See you, Tasty.

00:54:32.060 --> 00:54:35.960
He left the board for good.

00:54:35.960 --> 00:54:39.200
Occasionally, I would walk by the Tasty phone.

00:54:39.200 --> 00:54:44.320
But all I expected to find was maybe some loose change.

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:45.880
It was hopeless.

00:54:45.880 --> 00:54:55.560
The signs that the summer was ending were all around us.

00:54:55.560 --> 00:54:57.800
Do you get tan with you, stinky?

00:54:57.800 --> 00:55:04.090
We will battle next year.

00:55:04.090 --> 00:55:06.730
Finally, late one afternoon, there

00:55:06.730 --> 00:55:09.770
was nothing left to do by close the command center once

00:55:09.770 --> 00:55:10.970
and for all.

00:55:10.970 --> 00:55:18.300
I were closed the day.

00:55:18.300 --> 00:55:20.380
Could you please?

00:55:20.380 --> 00:55:21.780
Mr. Tasty.

00:55:21.780 --> 00:55:23.340
Hey, kiddos.

00:55:23.340 --> 00:55:24.980
Mr. Tasty, you're back.

00:55:24.980 --> 00:55:26.100
Where were you?

00:55:26.100 --> 00:55:27.140
Where?

00:55:27.140 --> 00:55:29.500
I think you know where I was.

00:55:29.500 --> 00:55:31.420
Ellen, right?

00:55:31.420 --> 00:55:34.740
I saw this on a telephone pole outside Biloxi.

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:39.100
And this one near Duluth seems everywhere I went.

00:55:39.100 --> 00:55:40.620
There I was.

00:55:40.620 --> 00:55:42.220
Why did you come back?

00:55:42.220 --> 00:55:43.060
Oh, I had to.

00:55:43.060 --> 00:55:46.420
I wanted to pick up my photographs.

00:55:46.420 --> 00:55:52.200
Oh, yeah, they're right here.

00:55:52.200 --> 00:55:54.200
I guess, you know, we looked at them.

00:55:54.200 --> 00:55:56.600
I kind of figured you did.

00:55:56.600 --> 00:55:58.120
How'd they turn out?

00:55:58.120 --> 00:56:01.640
Oh, hey, you ever been to the Statue of Liberty?

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:02.760
You should go.

00:56:02.760 --> 00:56:05.320
I pretended a blue tornado bar was the torch.

00:56:05.320 --> 00:56:06.920
I wish it was.

00:56:06.920 --> 00:56:09.320
Me too.

00:56:09.320 --> 00:56:10.960
We missed you, Mr. Tasty.

00:56:10.960 --> 00:56:13.320
Please, don't say that.

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:15.120
But why is it so terrible?

00:56:15.160 --> 00:56:18.840
Because every year on this day, the summer ends.

00:56:18.840 --> 00:56:21.080
And I always have to say goodbye.

00:56:21.080 --> 00:56:24.040
It's hard enough without having you kiddos missing me.

00:56:24.040 --> 00:56:25.120
Then don't go.

00:56:25.120 --> 00:56:27.080
I have to, Pete.

00:56:27.080 --> 00:56:28.960
I'm an ice cream man.

00:56:28.960 --> 00:56:30.800
I am what the summer is.

00:56:30.800 --> 00:56:35.160
Fireflies, thunderstorms, bucked sweat on the car seat.

00:56:35.160 --> 00:56:39.040
And when it all goes, I have to go with it.

00:56:39.040 --> 00:56:41.240
Couldn't you just stay a little bit longer?

00:56:41.240 --> 00:56:43.720
Well, I'll tell you what.

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:45.520
There's a little daylight left.

00:56:45.520 --> 00:56:48.480
What do you say you kiddos help me wax the tasting mobile?

00:56:48.480 --> 00:56:50.960
Didn't you say that was a one-man job?

00:56:50.960 --> 00:56:57.350
Not anymore.

00:56:57.350 --> 00:57:01.270
I guess we thought if we just kept waxing and waxing,

00:57:01.270 --> 00:57:03.550
